      {
        "type": "theory",
        "title": "ðŸ“š Theory: Basic Pronouns",
        "content": {
          "introduction": "Pronouns can be attached to verbs to show the subject of the verb (i.e., the person doing the verb) or the object of the sentence (i.e., the person the verb is being done to). To attach a pronoun to a verb, you remove the 'n' at the end of the pronoun and attach the remaining part to the verb. For example: 'An' means 'I' and 'dhi' means 'to go'. To say 'I go', you would say 'Adhi' - you remove the 'n' from 'An' and attach 'A' to the verb 'dhi'.",
          "phrases": [
            {
                "dholuo": "An + dhi = Adhi",
                "literal": "I + go = I go",
                "english": "I go",
                "notes": "Remove 'n' from 'An', attach 'A' to 'dhi'"
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "In + dhi = Idhi", 
                "literal": "You + go = You go",
                "english": "You go",
                "notes": "Remove 'n' from 'In', attach 'I' to 'dhi'"
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "En + dhi = Odhi",
                "literal": "He/She + goes = He/She goes",
                "english": "He/She goes",
                "notes": "The third person singular is unique. The 'e' turns to 'o'."
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "Wan + dhi = Wadhi",
                "literal": "We + go = We go",
                "english": "We go",
                "notes": "Remove 'n' from 'Wan', attach 'Wa' to 'dhi'"
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "Un + dhi = Udhi",
                "literal": "You (plural) + go = You go",
                "english": "You go",
                "notes": "Remove 'n' from 'Un', attach 'U' to 'dhi'"
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "Gin + dhi = Gidhi",
                "literal": "They + go = They go",
                "english": "They go",
                "notes": "Remove 'n' from 'Gin', attach 'Gi' to 'dhi'"
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "O + hero + wa = Oherowa", 
                "literal": "He/she + loves + us = He/she loves us",
                "english": "He/she loves us.",
                "notes": "Pronouns can also be attached at the end of verbs to show who the action is being done. In this case, you remove the 'n' from 'wan' and attach it to the end of the verb."
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "A + miyo + gi = Amiyogi", 
                "literal": "I + give + them = I give them",
                "english": "I give them.",
                "notes": "The pronoun at the beginning of the verb shows who is doing the action. The one at the end shows who the action is being done to."
              },
              {
                "dholuo": "Wa + moso + e = Wamose", 
                "literal": "We + greet + her (or him) = We greet her (or him).",
                "english": "We greet her",
                "notes": "Here, you remove the 'n' from 'Wan' and attach it to the front of the verb. You do the same with 'En' and attach it to the end of the verb."
              }
          ],
          "grammar_note": "The third person singular 'En' takes the form 'O' when it is the subject of the verb but the form 'e' when it is the object."
        }
      },
